  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the types of pain during pregnancy?",
  "response": "During pregnancy, women may experience various types of pain. These pains can be attributed to the many changes happening in their bodies. Here are some common types:\n\n1. **Morning Sickness**: Although not exactly pain, nausea and vomiting, especially during the first trimester, can be quite uncomfortable.\n\n2. **Back Pain**: As the pregnancy progresses, the growing belly can strain the back muscles, leading to pain. This is common in the lower back region.\n\n3. **Round Ligament Pain**: Sharp pain or pulling sensation in the lower abdomen or groin area, often caused by the stretching of ligaments that support the uterus.\n\n4. **Pelvic Pain**: Pressure and pain in the pelvic area due to the growing uterus.\n\n5. **Braxton Hicks Contractions**: These are irregular, usually painless or mildly uncomfortable contractions that can occur throughout pregnancy.\n\n6. **Headaches**: Hormonal changes and increased blood volume can lead to headaches.\n\n7. **Hip Pain**: Pain in the hip region due to the shifting of bones and muscles to accommodate the growing fetus.\n\n8. **Sciatica**: Pressure on the sciatic nerve can cause sharp, radiating pain in the lower back, buttocks, and down the legs.\n\n9. **Leg Cramps**: Often occurring at night, these can be due to changes in blood circulation and pressure from the growing uterus.\n\n10. **Carpal Tunnel Syndrome**: Tingling, numbness, or pain in the wrists and hands due to swelling that compresses the nerves.\n\n11. **Breast Tenderness**: Hormonal changes can cause breasts to feel sore and sensitive.\n\n12. **Heartburn and Indigestion**: Painful symptoms in the upper abdomen due to hormonal changes and pressure from the uterus.\n\n13. **Hemorrhoids**: Painful swellings due to increased pressure and blood flow.\n\n14. **Vulvar Varicosities**: Pain and swelling in the vulvar region due to varicose veins.\n\nIt's important for pregnant women to communicate any pain or discomfort with their healthcare provider to ensure proper management and rule out more serious conditions.",
